## Competitive Landscape: Focus Bear vs Other Productivity Apps

## Apps Researched
- Freedom
- Cold Turkey
- Tiimo
- Routinery
- Focus Bear

---

## What makes Focus Bear different from these apps?

Freedom and Cold Turkey function as purely distraction blockers - meaning they
are exceptional at blocking out websites and apps. However, that is essentially
all they do.

Tiimo and Routinery are primarily routine/schedule/habit setting apps. They help
plan your routines and send reminder notifications. However, they seem less
strict in terms of enforcing habits compared to Focus Bear.

Focus Bear tends to encourage real-time habit engagement, rather than just
gently reminding you to track your progress.

Overall, biggest difference with Focus Bear compared to all the others, is the
focus on helping neurodivergent people specifically. It combimes active
distraction blocking and routine guidance into one app, rather than focusing
specifically on one aspect.

---

## Why would a user choose Focus Bear over competitors?

To reiterate the point made above:

If I was someone who has ADHD or struggle with executive function, I would find
Focus Bear more suitable. The other apps is working with the assumption that I
already have the discipline to properly use them. Therefore, it doesn't hold
your hand in terms of guiding you.

I'd choose Focus Bear specifically if I already know that the other apps doesn't
work for me as a user. It's for people who need more than a nudge- they need an
app to strictly guide them when they don't have the willpower or natural ability
to focus.

---

## A feature competitors have that Focus Bear currently lacks

Compared to the other apps, Focus bear currrently lacks the ability to socially
engage with other users in a session/group setting. Specifically, it's currently
very solo-focused.

A potential problem with this is that having no external (social) motivation
like sharing routines or competing in maintaining streaks could make for a very
isolating experience. The Focus Bear app can benefit from sharing acheivements
or joining a group block; because for many ADHD people, having a buddy is
considered a very effective focus strategy.

---

## One improvement Focus Bear could make

Right now, I found the onboarding flow a little overwhelming and confusing.
During initial onboarding, you are presented with a 'blank' canvas of setting up
your own habits and routines.

However, this may seem very overwhelming to a user, due to a lack of proper
onboarding process. You still have to design your routine - which sort of
contradicts Focus Bear's ethos enforcing a strict routine.

A potential improvement can be having a more clear and concise onboarding
process, like a demonstration and walkthrough for all the features on the app.
Potentially an AI bot can be used to help ask questions to help gauge an initial
routine for you. Hence, you can have a 'starting kit' which you can adjust as
you become more familiar with the interface.